      "content": "```python\ndef specialized_sort(data: list[float]) -> list[float]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Sorts a list of floats in ascending order, handling specific precision edge cases.\n\n    Args:\n        data (list[float]): The list of floats to sort.\n\n    Returns:\n        list[float]: The sorted list of floats.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Use a custom sorting function that handles precision edge cases\n    def custom_sort_key(x):\n        # Handle zero-sign issues\n        if x == 0:\n            return 0\n        # Handle quantization issues\n        if abs(x - round(x)) < 1e-9:\n            return round(x)\n        return x\n\n    # Sort the list using the custom key\n    return sorted(data, key=custom_sort_key)\n```\nThis function uses a custom sorting key that handles precision edge cases. It checks for zero-sign issues and quantization issues by comparing the float value with its rounded value. If the difference is less than 1e-9, it rounds the value to the nearest integer. Otherwise, it uses the original float value as the sorting key.\n\nThis function should pass the test suite with the specific inputs you mentioned, including `[0.1, 0.2,",
